Yes, you're correct! With source generators, you can not only create files in the output directory but also set the file metadata to include the generated files as part of the project's output. This way, the generated files will be automatically copied to the output directory when the project is built.

To achieve this, you need to use the `context.AddSource` method in your `ISourceGenerator` implementation. This method allows you to add new source files to the compilation, and you can specify the file metadata, including the "copy to output" behavior.

Here's an example of how you can do it:

```csharp
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis;
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.Text;

[Generator]
public class MySourceGenerator : ISourceGenerator
{
    public void Initialize(GeneratorInitializationContext context)
    {
        // No initialization required for this example
    }

    public void Execute(GeneratorExecutionContext context)
    {
        // Generate the content for the file
        string fileContent = "This is the metadata content.";

        // Create a SourceText object from the file content
        SourceText sourceText = SourceText.From(fileContent, Encoding.UTF8);

        // Set the file metadata
        string fileName = "metadata.txt";
        string fileExtension = Path.GetExtension(fileName);
        string hintPath = fileName;

        // Add the source file to the compilation with the specified metadata
        context.AddSource(
            fileName,
            sourceText,
            new SourceFileMetadataBuilder()
                .WithCopyToOutputDirectory(true)
                .WithBuildAction(fileExtension == ".cs" ? BuildAction.Compile : BuildAction.None)
                .WithHintPath(hintPath)
                .Build());
    }
}
```

Here's what's happening in the code above:

1. We generate the content for the file as a string (`fileContent`).
2. We create a `SourceText` object from the file content using `SourceText.From`.
3. We set the file metadata, including the file name (`fileName`), file extension (`fileExtension`), and hint path (`hintPath`).
4. We use the `context.AddSource` method to add the source file to the compilation.
5. We pass the file name, `SourceText` object, and a `SourceFileMetadataBuilder` object to `context.AddSource`.
6. In the `SourceFileMetadataBuilder`, we set the `WithCopyToOutputDirectory` property to `true`, which tells the compiler to copy the generated file to the output directory.
7. We also set the `BuildAction` based on the file extension. If the file extension is `.cs`, we set the `BuildAction` to `Compile`, which means the file will be compiled. Otherwise, we set the `BuildAction` to `None`, which means the file will be copied to the output directory without being compiled.
8. Finally, we set the `HintPath` property, which is used by Visual Studio to determine the location of the file in the project.

With this approach, the generated file (`metadata.txt`) will be included in the project's output and automatically copied to the output directory when the project is built. Additionally, if the file extension is `.cs`, the file will be compiled along with the rest of the project's source code.

Note that the `SourceFileMetadataBuilder` class provides various other properties that you can set, such as `WithEmitMetadataOnly`, `WithEmbedInteropTypes`, and more. You can explore these properties and set them as needed for your specific use case.

